Taking note of what @Ken_barns @cdod63 @cmeinel have said;
To me it would not count as a "public vote" unless all the "public" is able to vote, which would require lists of who is eligible to vote, and locations where all those eligible can caste a ballot.  If the public do not know if they are eligible to vote or not, or if those eligible to vote do not know how and where to caste their ballot I would not count it as a public vote. Nor would I count it if polling stations allowed people to vote without carrying out a check to see that they were entitled to vote (that would just be a poorly conducted opinion poll). 
A public vote therefore would require polling stations that were advertised to the public as such. If the public are informed of where the polling station are and when they are open, then that information would be known to the police. If the police know when and where polling will take place they can prevent access to these places, remove list of eligible voters, arrest those administering the votes and confiscate ballot boxes, The public could demonstrate against this, but I can't see how the results of any vote if the voters have to fight their way past the police could be considered valid, unless there was an incredibly high turnout 80% with more than 50% of the total electorate supporting one side and no chance of vote tampering. So unless the police let the vote take place I think it would not count as a "public vote".

